Title: Mr.
Traveling Companions and other notes: The New York Times, Monday, May 10, 1915, page 6: “Mrs. Davy Kinshott of 21 Vista Avenue, Dongan Hills, S. I., wife of an assistant steward, accompanied by her young son, stayed in the Cunard offices all day awaiting news of her husband.”

Title: Mr.
Traveling Companions and other notes: Born in Belfast, Ireland to Robert and Margaret Jane Pinkerton, married Eliza Jane Clokey.  They lived at 40 Linacre Road, Liverpool.

Title: Mr.
Traveling Companions and other notes: See article, The New York Times, Wednesday, May 26, 1915, page 4, in which he was reported as having said he found two bombs on Deck A just before the ship sailed. The Cunard Line officials ridiculed this idea.

Title: Master
Traveling Companions and other notes: George was assistant cook in first class. Age 17 (or 16?). George was a friend to Charles Westbury, second cook,q.v. Lived on Oakes Street in Liverpool. Retired to a sailor’s home in the 1970’s. Mentioned in Hickey/Smith on pages 52+, 101, 171, 195, 206, 230, 314.

Title: Mr.
Traveling Companions and other notes: Joseph was George’s father. Suffered from bronchitis. Went down with the ship. Mentioned in Hickey/Smith on pages 53, 171, 206 and 230.
